            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Lee\u2019s story began not in a sleek corporate boardroom, but amidst the fragrant aisles of his parents' small grocery store in the Sunset District. The son of hardworking Taiwanese immigrants, he spent his youth stocking shelves and managing the register, learning the fundamentals of retail through observation and necessity. While his parents hoped he\u2019d become a doctor or engineer, David was fascinated by the quiet language of products on a shelf and the psychology of a sale.\n\nHe channeled his ambition into academics, earning a business degree from UC Berkeley. The corporate world beckoned, and David climbed the ladder steadily, but a layoff during the 2008 recession proved to be a pivotal turning point. Humbled and forced to freelance, he developed a grittier, more intuitive understanding of the market that a stable corporate job had never taught him. This resilience eventually led him to a top MBA program and landed him his current role as Director of Merchandising for a major apparel brand.\n\nToday, David\u2019s life is a curated balance. His 2.1-mile Muni ride from his Hayes Valley condo to his downtown office is a cherished ritual of podcasts and people-watching. Even with a $215,000 income, he values the city\u2019s public fabric. He shares his life with his partner of ten years, Marcus, a landscape architect. Their weekends are spent exploring the Ferry Building Farmers Market, hosting dinner parties, or escaping to hike in Marin.\n\nAt 46, David feels a gentle pull away from the corporate grind. While a Vice President title is within reach, his true aspiration is to come full circle. He dreams of one day opening a small, thoughtfully curated home goods store with Marcus, a modern echo of his parents\u2019 humble market. For David, success is no longer just about climbing higher, but about building something personal, meaningful, and deeply connected to the city that has shaped every chapter of his life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, meticulously creating a pyramid of grass jelly cans in his parents' Sunset market. His father, apron dusted with flour, gently rearranged them. \"Face out, always face out,\" he said in Mandarin. Not a scolding, but a lesson. In that moment, David understood the cans weren't just inventory; they were speaking to customers. It wasn't about being tidy; it was about telling a story. This quiet language became his first business lesson, a foundation that corporate strategy could never replace.\n\n2.\nThe words \"corporate restructuring\" hung in the sterile air of the conference room in late 2008. He remembers the weight of the cardboard box holding a sad fern and a framed diploma. Walking out onto Market Street felt like stepping off a cliff. The sharp sting of failure was terrifying, but it burned away his arrogance. That public humbling forced him to build a resilience and an intuition for survival that no MBA program could ever teach. He wasn't a title anymore; he was just David.\n\n3.\nFive years ago, on a foggy Saturday, he watched Marcus gently select heirloom tomatoes at the Ferry Building. \"Look at this,\" Marcus had said, holding one up like a jewel. \"This is real.\" In that simple, unprompted moment, David\u2019s dream of a store clicked into place. It wouldn't be just his\u2014it would be theirs. A space built on their shared appreciation for beautiful, honest things. It was the moment a personal ambition became a shared life.\n\n4.\nJust last Tuesday on the N Judah, he watched a musician coax a melody from a worn guitar a few seats away. His podcast fell silent in his ears. He saw the city's entire story in that car: the student, the tourist, the elder. It was a richer, more authentic world than the one waiting in his high-rise office. That 2.1-mile ride wasn't a commute; it was a daily reminder of the grounded, tangible life he increasingly craved beyond the corporate ladder.\n\n5.\nFor his 46th birthday, he visited his parents in the Sunset. His mother, her hands now soft from retirement, served tea in a simple porcelain cup. He recognized it as unsold stock from their old store. He pictured it on a beautiful oak shelf in the shop he and Marcus dreamed of\u2014not as old inventory, but as a curated piece of a story. He felt a profound sense of continuity, understanding his future wasn\u2019t a rejection of his past, but a modern, loving tribute to it."
